{"questionId":"9066449","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p><span style=\"background-color:#ffffff;\">Physical properties of elements vary according to atomic number. Sections 6 to 9 of the data<br>booklet list some of these properties.</span></p>\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\"><span style=\"background-color:#ffffff;\">Melting points and boiling points of elements 1 to 95</span></p>\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\"><span style=\"background-color:#ffffff;\"><img src=\"__IMG__/7e051c51fe7dbc81de0824cb07025b4c6bcc350d.png\" width=\"698\" height=\"443\"></span></p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p><span style=\"background-color:#ffffff;\">Describe the density trend across periods 4 and 5 of the periodic table.</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"background-color:#ffffff;\"><img src=\"__IMG__/90987cd0827ccce3c1eb97061d72e36f4e76786e.png\" width=\"707\" height=\"297\"></span></p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p><span style=\"background-color:#ffffff;\">density increases «to a maximum in the transition elements» <em><strong>AND</strong> </em>then decreases &nbsp; &nbsp; <strong>[✔]</strong></span></p>","meta":{"questionId":"9066449","referenceCode":"19M.3.hl.TZ1.1b(i)","subjectId":"45-dp-chemistry-last-assessment-2024","title":"Describe the density trend across periods 4 and 5 of the periodic table.","paper":"3","level":"HL","questionNumber":"b(i)","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 1]","breadcrumbLabels":["Core","Core","Topic 11: Measurement and data processing","11.2 Graphical techniques","Core","Topic 11: Measurement and data processing"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":2}